<TR BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"><TD COLSPAN=3><TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="LEFT">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl?day=8&show_all=1"><font size=2>&lt;&lt;&lt;&nbsp;DEC&nbsp;8</font></a></TD><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="CENTER"><a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl"><font size=2>HOME</font></a></TD><TD ALIGN="CENTER"><a class="addthis_button" href="http://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=250&amp;pub=xa-4b157e7f1b908808"><img src="http://s7.addthis.com/static/btn/v2/lg-share-en.gif" width="125" height="16" alt="Bookmark and Share" style="border:0"/></a><script type="text/javascript" src="http://s7.addthis.com/js/250/addthis_widget.js#pub=xa-4b157e7f1b908808"></script></TD><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="RIGHT"><a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl?day=10&show_all=1"><font size=2>DEC&nbsp;10&nbsp;&gt;&gt;&gt;</font></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></TD></TR>
<TR HEIGHT=5><TD COLSPAN=3 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=5 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD>
<TD BACKGROUND="/black6.png">
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5><TR><TD>
	<TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=130 HEIGHT=130 SRC="chocs/choc_day_9.png" ALT="chocolate"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=190 SRC="globes/advent_globe_9.png" ALT="snowglobe"><table cellpadding=10 align="center" background="/black4.png" width=430><TR><TD><center><font size=6 color="#ffff00"><b><i>POWER DRIFT</i></b></font><br><font size=3 color="red"><b><i>16 days to Christmas</i></b></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><p>
Don't worry - this may indeed be the fourth driving game to feature in
this Advent Calendar, but rest assured there aren't many others! I
don't mind admitting it, I'm a sucker for a good race game, and with
the basic aim of <i>Power Drift</i> being to finish each stage third or
better, it was always onto a winner with me, especially considering
that such a race-like structure was actually quite a rarity for
into-the-screen driving games. Usually they're just time trials,
checkpointing before a counter reaches zero.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE ALIGN="right"><TR><TD VALIGN="top"><TABLE  WIDTH=205 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d9_1989_ad1.png" target="1989_ad1.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d9_1989_ad1_small.jpg" WIDTH=205 HEIGHT=150></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>A low-key teaser advert...</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE></TD><TD>&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD><TD VALIGN="top"><TABLE  WIDTH=214 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d9_1989_ad12.png" target="1989_ad12.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d9_1989_ad12_small.jpg" WIDTH=214 HEIGHT=150></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>...although the double-page ad was suitably exciting.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE></TD></TR></TABLE>It was the racing aspect which the arcade version of <i>Power Drift</i>
played up to. Across the top of the screen you would see pictures of
all fifteen racers, and this list would change as they overtook one
another, waving them off as they did so. A racing game which kept
track of each individual race car wasn't new - <i>WEC Le Mans</i> did that,
too, adding a new level of realism to the genre, but it was <i>Power
Drift</i> which added personality to them.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Not much of a gimmick, I hear you say? Yep, I agree, which is why
<i>Power Drift</i> also added a third dimension to an into-the-screen racing
game: height. We're not talking your usual hills and valleys here.
We're talking steep bridges, ramps, humps, spirals - the works. On the
arcade version you got a top-down map of the current level which
showed this perfectly, although falling off a raised level is also a
good way to see the new depth! This lead to some spectacular crash
sequences when you slightly misjudge a thirty-foot jump!
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="left"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/1CwxtppSLAc&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/1CwxtppSLAc&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>YS Power Drift Demo</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">An exclusive level, no less! I played this to death - I think it was the drifting corners that sold it to me. <b><i>(4:56)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1CwxtppSLAc" target="1CwxtppSLAc">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE ALIGN="right" WIDTH=300 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d9_1989_pre4.png" target="1989_pre4.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d9_1989_pre4_small.jpg" WIDTH=300 HEIGHT=208></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>SU knew how to tease us: lots of loverly screenshots.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>It was YS who beat everybody to the punch this time around, getting a
playable demo of a one-off exclusive level which showed the basic
features of the game: lots of twists and turns, a couple of bridges,
plus the other drivers. It was just challenging enough to draw you in,
and was surprisingly difficult to win the stage initially. It was
silent, it wasn't part of the finished game, and yet I found it
totally compulsive.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;All the gimmicks were sucking me into it, and I just had to get the
finished game. OK, so the finished product had a few flaws, like dodgy
collision detection at times, unfair opponents who'd sometimes hog the
narrow bridges, and sometimes on the 128K version the tune would drop
out completely (explained away as the Speccy CPU working really hard
at that point), but what was there was as addictive and challenging as
hell. The sheer variety of courses and the ability to select which
ones to play seriously delayed any onset of boredom, although it was
inevitably a multi-load.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Aside from it's spiritual predecessor <i>WEC Le Mans</i>, it's the best
driving game out there which has realistic opponents which you have to
have an overtaking strategy with, compared to most race games which
are exercises in advanced dodging.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD></TR><TR><TD><IMG SRC="chocs/voxpop.png" ALIGN="LEFT"><br><IMG SRC="pngs/andrewrollings_small.jpg" ALIGN="RIGHT"><TABLE BACKGROUND="/black7.png"><TR><TD><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#ffff00"><B><I>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;ANDREW ROLLINGS&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I></B></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><br>
<b>Here's retro-book giant Andrew Rollings, who made the insightful decision to include a certain webmaster's abridged history of the Speccy industry in his ZX Spectrum Book. Whaddayamean "who?"?!</b><br><br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Who are you and what are you up to?</font></i></b><br>
Andrew Rollings, and writing this email... I really should be writing a book though!
<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="left"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/3666uiV0Pxk&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/3666uiV0Pxk&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Thames TV Continuity and Adverts Christmas 1989</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">Ahhh yes... remember when it was cool to pretend that banks would give you "a new kind of bank account"? Plus a glorious car advert. <b><i>(4:14)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3666uiV0Pxk" target="3666uiV0Pxk">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>

<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Favourite cracker gift (aside from fortune-telling fish, naturally)?</font></i></b><br>
The little china animals.
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Favourite Christmas Song?</font></i></b><br>
Baby, it's cold outside.
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Best memory of Christmases gone by?<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="right"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/HLAbTbGQcr8&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/HLAbTbGQcr8&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>InnerSpace Trailer</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">This seemed to be always playing on a video recorder at school one Christmas. <b><i>(1:27)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HLAbTbGQcr8" target="HLAbTbGQcr8">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>
</font></i></b><br>
Getting my Spectrum, of course :)
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Best Speccy Christmas memory?</font></i></b><br>
Thinking that I only had one game to play (<i>Pimania</i>) that I had bought a couple of months earlier, only to find my sister and mother had bought me <i>Pssst</i> and <i>Jetpac</i> respectively.
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Favourite Quality Street chocolate?</font></i></b><br>
Either the green triangle or the long yellow chewy one... They sell giant ones now, don't they? Mmmmmm...
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Best present ever?</font></i></b><br>
Hmmm... Good question. It's either got to be my Spectrum (of course) or the set of plush Pacman ghosts my wife bought me a couple of years ago.
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Speccy game you most looked forward to?</font></i></b><br>
<i>Underwurlde</i> and <i>Knight Lore</i>... Couldn't just pick one - I was equally excited about both. Of course, when I eventually got them, it was <i>Knight Lore</i> that got all the play time.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD></TR>
</TABLE><p>
